<subSubSection id="23DEF19A088A22073779789D825E5049" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="7EB6C9441DE4BB6D7D29DB13AF872E63" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="A5005179893D87808FDCE32A7A5EF5D6" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Xanthosarus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xanthosarus">Xanthosarus</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65AEA7AE3A999E15C96E721B688AB69A" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="F0CB17845364CD15763B9260225CFF6D" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis and description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E37D231B84A4D9C92C238DCE8D7E1C10" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Females: Most females of 
<taxonomicName id="D1C07427935D0E54F992748EC4F73D76" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Xanthosarus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xanthosarus">Xanthosarus</taxonomicName>
have a typical, broad mandible (Fig. 35) with tooth 1 larger than other teeth, without apical brush of hairs in the grooves around the base of tooth 1. In such females there is a well-visible, continuous cutting edge in the third interspace and a partial cutting edge in the second interspace (Fig. 35), the third interspace is deeper than the other interspaces, and the two upper teeth close together or poorly separated, so that the mandible is not clearly 5-toothed. Such females will be easy to identify using the present key. The mandible of 
<taxonomicName id="F64CF16442E83570C3D4A8302A45EC74" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile nigriventris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriventris">Megachile nigriventris</taxonomicName>
Schenck, 1868 (Fig. 36) [and to some extend of 
<taxonomicName id="01AA3A85E34A737945BBB4ADD5620995" genus="M." lsidName="M. willughbiella" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="willughbiella">M. willughbiella</taxonomicName>
(Kirby, 1802): Fig. 37] is different, less robust, with the cutting edges little visible in front view; the upper tooth is broadly truncate and the condition is intermediate between the 4-toothed and the 5-toothed conditions. In all Palearctic species of 
<taxonomicName id="FA32CFAB2F706217D154542480CA9973" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Xanthosarus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xanthosarus">Xanthosarus</taxonomicName>
, the clypeus is finely and densely punctured, regularly convex (Figs 35-37) unlike the condition found in most females of 
<taxonomicName id="11EB7B55C1D461409B215470F05E1D18" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megachile</taxonomicName>
s. str. The scopa is mostly orange-red basally, sometimes nearly entirely black (
<taxonomicName id="A71B1EA41478F36CCCAFA7F9409FD6EF" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriventris" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="nigriventris">M. nigriventris</taxonomicName>
) or yellow-white on sternites 2 and 3 [e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="9A7AFDB6FE70375914E529B13F8EEC98" genus="M." lsidName="M. maritima" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maritima">M. maritima</taxonomicName>
(Kirby, 1802)], rarely entirely yellowish-white. The sterna lack the apical fringe of hairs beneath the scopa, unlike in most 
<taxonomicName id="85E348574D98DB77E99663036DFD877B" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Eutricharaea)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Eutricharaea">Eutricharaea</taxonomicName>
or in 
<taxonomicName id="93F87E86FBA9A209F14B8099CB6E0734" genus="M." lsidName="M. (Eurymella) patellimana" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="patellimana" subGenus="Eurymella">M. (Eurymella) patellimana</taxonomicName>
. Males: In males of 
<taxonomicName id="5C41820470A5B9AF9E58AD9BECF076A7" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Xanthosarus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xanthosarus">Xanthosarus</taxonomicName>
the front coxal spine is always well developed; often there is a field of modified, short, orange bristles on the surface anteriorly to the spine, but such field may be lacking (e.g. in 
<taxonomicName id="2B8A904F8A6CDD8FD73D5E3C6510C829" genus="M." lsidName="M. analis" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="analis">M. analis</taxonomicName>
Nylander, 1852). The front tarsi are always yellow or white, from relatively narrow [e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="79B93BBB0DE1162500D8CBC16CE0DAC1" genus="M." lsidName="M. analis" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="analis">M. analis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D38A60765756B36E0CEEBC365C83602C" genus="M." lsidName="M. circumcincta" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="circumcincta">M. circumcincta</taxonomicName>
(Kirby, 1802)] to conspicuously enlarged [e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="8937C7DBDA21AC3780295A4074AD0551" genus="M." lsidName="M. lagopoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="lagopoda">M. lagopoda</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus, 1761), 
<taxonomicName id="D7961E7985040DFAB7ECA61BFE1A303E" genus="M." lsidName="M. maritima" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maritima">M. maritima</taxonomicName>
]; the first tarsal segment is mostly strongly concave interiorly, except in 
<taxonomicName id="4319FAF05608E38E89B586594229F80F" genus="M." lsidName="M. analis" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="analis">M. analis</taxonomicName>
. The mandible is either 3-toothed (
<taxonomicName id="F2672717C42FBE61B2A29F56B1D60BDC" genus="M." lsidName="M. lapogoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="lapogoda">M. lapogoda</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5B99366382129D33CA125C771E22A3A9" genus="M." lsidName="M. maritima" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maritima">M. maritima</taxonomicName>
) or more commonly 4-toothed; the inferior margin always has a pointed process directed posteriorly; in some large species, this process is particularly large and glabrous, except for some orange hairs apically. The disc of T6 is mostly not covered by white vestiture; the preapical carina of T6 is bilobed or weakly denticulate. The apical margin of T6 often lacks a lateral tooth (a small tooth is sometimes present, e.g. in 
<taxonomicName id="D727B4955C622B52AA75D62F24D4D660" genus="M." lsidName="M. maritima" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maritima">M. maritima</taxonomicName>
). The apex of T7 is usually produced to a small tooth medially, although the tooth is small in some species; in other species T7 is weakly trifid. The gonostylus is variable, either simple or strongly bifid, but this character does not clearly segregate groups.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EB6A77A83749936283377FC334A3EFC3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="species composition">
<paragraph id="1B844243F8180833738AA2CA7E9BBA3F" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Species composition.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1C3D14F7E2A4FB5D42FE401D03DC055C" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
There are at least seven species in the western Palearctic: 
<taxonomicName id="63CCE0056DB260A106D6C7D5CBC6A16E" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile analis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">Megachile analis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="869611FE157829B2681416B2D3E429D8" genus="M." lsidName="M. circumcincta" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="circumcincta">M. circumcincta</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FC677387EB72FFEE1958D5613E6ACC56" genus="M." lsidName="M. diabolica" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="diabolica">M. diabolica</taxonomicName>
Friese, 1898, 
<taxonomicName id="3C4DF93BEA67DE368126688144453526" genus="M." lsidName="M. lagopoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="lagopoda">M. lagopoda</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="8F7F0D98CFE8924C16C749DBEC00A47A" genus="M." lsidName="M. maritima" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maritima">M. maritima</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FFC11D90120BDBAA9A0DABC5B942FB8D" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriventris" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="nigriventris">M. nigriventris</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C365154F0907BAE6593E5143A8BC06B4" genus="M." lsidName="M. willughbiella" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="willughbiella">M. willughbiella</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="F9F7584F4FBF2C93B82485EBDB699F7B" genus="M." lsidName="M. fulvimana" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="fulvimana">M. fulvimana</taxonomicName>
Eversmann, 1852 has been mentioned from Southeastern Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="CC89FFA99E22CAA66B3E6093944281BE" author="Banaszak, J" journalOrPublisher="Bydgoszcz University, Bydgoszcz" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" title="Megachilid bees of Europe (Hymenoptera, Apoidea, Megachilidae)." year="2001">Banaszak and Romasenko 2001</bibRefCitation>
); this species is known to me only from Central Asia. 
<taxonomicName id="6FA965D5EA9B218C342A5CAEA042024E" genus="M." lsidName="M. mguildensis" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="mguildensis">M. mguildensis</taxonomicName>
Benoist, 1940, from Algeria and Morocco, apparently closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="A6F7BEC895609799AFF7F1D398FEFFDB" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriventris" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="nigriventris">M. nigriventris</taxonomicName>
, may either represent a distinct species or merely a color morph of 
<taxonomicName id="4509EB0C306A81C2217832FCCFEB2E57" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriventris" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="nigriventris">M. nigriventris</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="AC6DBDC8125FF9E89FFF4B15688B25A8" author="Oezbek, H" journalOrPublisher="Turkish Journal of Entomology" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="157 - 174" title="A preliminary review of the Megachilidae of Turkey, Part IV. Megachilini and Lithurgini (Hymenoptera: Apoidea)." volume="18" year="1994">
<normalizedToken id="4216B77182EF5FC787DEEDDE47B37BAB" originalValue="Özbek">Oezbek</normalizedToken>
and Zanden (1994)
</bibRefCitation>
further cite 
<taxonomicName id="C59880627ED235195F521095CDF0D96E" genus="M." lsidName="M. metatarsalis" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="metatarsalis">M. metatarsalis</taxonomicName>
Morawitz, 1894 from Turkey; this species is unknown to me. The status of 
<taxonomicName id="080C8060C513E198CCE666BFB0FB159B" genus="M." lsidName="M. fulvescens" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="fulvescens">M. fulvescens</taxonomicName>
Smith, 1853 from Sicily is unclear; it is unlikely to represent a species distinct from those listed above; its description (&quot;the pollen brush is of golden hue towards the base, becoming bright fulvous at the apex&quot;) suggests 
<taxonomicName id="9C80A2510D9212CA2F26E0EF224426E9" genus="M." lsidName="M. maritima" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maritima">M. maritima</taxonomicName>
. Similarly, the status of 
<taxonomicName id="136B0853A245216E0BBCBBEAEB0F5E97" genus="M." lsidName="M. maacki" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maacki">M. maacki</taxonomicName>
Radoszkowski, 1874 remains in doubt; 
<bibRefCitation id="4D4320BA5A373BE47C8FED04668E6D0E" author="Scheuchl, E" journalOrPublisher="Apollo Books, Stenstrup, Denmark" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" title="Illustrierte Bestimmungstabellen der Wildbienen Deutschlands und Oesterreichs. Band II: Megachilidae - Melittidae. Second, revised edition." year="2006">Scheuchl (2006)</bibRefCitation>
provides a description of the male and the female and differentiates this species from 
<taxonomicName id="2395489988CA44999F1FE0667CAAB843" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriventris" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="nigriventris">M. nigriventris</taxonomicName>
. However, no lectotype has been designated. Of the possible syntypes that I could examine (ISZP), one male agrees with the original description and does not appear specifically distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="CFE5BED5F50D8564E071831722EEDA61" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriventris" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="nigriventris">M. nigriventris</taxonomicName>
. Possibly, 
<taxonomicName id="A17D30352D94741B700EFC264ED5438E" genus="M." lsidName="M. maacki" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="maacki">M. maacki</taxonomicName>
represents an Eastern Palearctic, geographic form of 
<taxonomicName id="DA269865606A4517688FB7EE46AD6C31" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriventris" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species" species="nigriventris">M. nigriventris</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="E8BFE15EBD02BB21A29839B8755DDB96" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Xanthosarus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xanthosarus">Xanthosarus</taxonomicName>
appears particularly diverse in the mountains of Central Asia and in Mongolia, where several additional species occur.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F2B76958F5E62A6C457B6D58C9828730" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="19DE9C2B102AF693B6E2335D4825AD45" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1BC3DBB5DC7DC554FE8EA864E2F67442" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Most species of the sugbenus 
<taxonomicName id="FB2320C08C0EC0A6CEF4E6275480812E" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Xanthosarus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xanthosarus">Xanthosarus</taxonomicName>
place their brood cells made of cut leaves in underground burrows or more rarely under stones; the females appear 
<pageBreakToken id="EDF949890D45B815E9F830A536885E32" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" start="start">to</pageBreakToken>
dig the burrows themselves (
<bibRefCitation id="E3A45ABDD9DC529EF13AFF7F9992862C" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Ulmer, Stuttgart" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" title="Die Wildbienen Baden-Wuerttembergs." year="1989">Westrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
, and references therein; 
<bibRefCitation id="20D83058466A4C0D83AAF875970A00BD" author="Hartmann, P" journalOrPublisher="Linzer Biologische Beitraege" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="349 - 364" title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Biologie und Verbreitung der Megachilediabolica Friese 1898 mit Erstbeschreibung des Maennchens." volume="30" year="1998">Hartmann and Arens 1998</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="E7FAECF40337DB4DF8F15D45D4C2B961" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile nigriventris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriventris">Megachile nigriventris</taxonomicName>
digs burrows only in decaying wood (
<bibRefCitation id="80300C0BF48289DDDF1F8695D61E61A2" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Ulmer, Stuttgart" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" title="Die Wildbienen Baden-Wuerttembergs." year="1989">Westrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="0D019C890DBC35ACCE883E15E9EEF103" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Dubitzky 2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="0C35F432149770DE012791D456CB305E" author="Reichholf, JH" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der zoologischen Gesellschaft braunau" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="199 - 201" title="Ein ungewoehnlicher Nistplatz der Schwarzbaeuchigen Blattschneiderbiene Megachilenigriventris am unteren Inn." volume="8" year="2002">Reichholf 2002</bibRefCitation>
), while 
<taxonomicName id="2B124B4D60415E48A5500F12C75587FF" genus="M." lsidName="M. willughbiella" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="willughbiella">M. willughbiella</taxonomicName>
either digs burrows in decaying wood or uses existing cavities such as vacant 
<taxonomicName id="4C87752F37383C8E4440A1CBEBE70ACE" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Anthophora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthophora" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anthophora</taxonomicName>
cells (
<bibRefCitation id="704CD6DF6E9D06A42C2FFB2E6284A875" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Ulmer, Stuttgart" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" title="Die Wildbienen Baden-Wuerttembergs." year="1989">Westrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
, and references therein; 
<bibRefCitation id="E6E871E37872CC908D83E5820CFA4AC6" author="Mueller, A" journalOrPublisher="Naturbuch Verlag, Augsburg" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" title="Bienen. Mitteleuropaeische Gattungen, Lebensweise, Beobachtung." year="1997">
<normalizedToken id="E8C5D0C46BDCD60CBE6CB844B5E03DFE" originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
et al. 1997
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="D18F6EDDAD80677DF1C92D929306F245" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile analis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">Megachile analis</taxonomicName>
is unusual in that it uses thin bark fragments and not leaves for the construction of the cells (
<bibRefCitation id="47CE006A835177ACDD791B5C41D6E422" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Ulmer, Stuttgart" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" title="Die Wildbienen Baden-Wuerttembergs." year="1989">Westrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
, and references therein); leaf discs are also used by this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AD783F263720436BA5C5BBD469F4F4BA" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName id="C9BBD1FCAC417E711208018B0DA99284" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile nigriventris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriventris">Megachile nigriventris</taxonomicName>
is likely oligolectic on 
<taxonomicName id="F148906FB86B93F55EE4DCC38B6B178B" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Fabaceae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2DF2C437C4B1B0D195ADB237A775FE3A" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Ulmer, Stuttgart" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" title="Die Wildbienen Baden-Wuerttembergs." year="1989">Westrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="8D804947767D7AD91E173664667E9986" author="Mueller, A" journalOrPublisher="Naturbuch Verlag, Augsburg" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" title="Bienen. Mitteleuropaeische Gattungen, Lebensweise, Beobachtung." year="1997">
<normalizedToken id="D3D697D534000690371C30320B7D3042" originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
et al. 1997
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="272AFDD5189936D800B91650754EC7BE" genus="M." lsidName="M. diabolica" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="diabolica">M. diabolica</taxonomicName>
possibly on 
<taxonomicName id="9AF3D99B3EB0551554A1523C902F0D8F" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Campanulaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="0037E923E400AD01A4B8338D622D4808" author="Hartmann, P" journalOrPublisher="Linzer Biologische Beitraege" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="349 - 364" title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Biologie und Verbreitung der Megachilediabolica Friese 1898 mit Erstbeschreibung des Maennchens." volume="30" year="1998">Hartmann and Arens 1998</bibRefCitation>
); 
<taxonomicName id="BACB60347702448A8040815383E099BA" genus="M." lsidName="M. analis" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="analis">M. analis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="90C14607991812AC0A67BD993242EE37" genus="M." lsidName="M. willughbiella" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="willughbiella">M. willughbiella</taxonomicName>
are polylectic but show a preference for 
<taxonomicName id="FAF39214E1440BF5573159C40353B2C6" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Fabaceae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="894645BE747EE9A0BD3CB358F794E3DE" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Campanulaceae</taxonomicName>
, as well as for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="8BF7C26E61C2ACB1309BB12DB4134C66" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium" order="Myrtales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Epilobium</taxonomicName>
by 
<taxonomicName id="4F8D2EED498B13972A103584CA9E5767" genus="M." lsidName="M. willughbiella" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="willughbiella">M. willughbiella</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E3C27CA59A157537598F6E52B82FCC07" author="Westrich, P" journalOrPublisher="Ulmer, Stuttgart" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" title="Die Wildbienen Baden-Wuerttembergs." year="1989">Westrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="717265CF222C1E7A011488DE3E035E52" author="Mueller, A" journalOrPublisher="Naturbuch Verlag, Augsburg" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" title="Bienen. Mitteleuropaeische Gattungen, Lebensweise, Beobachtung." year="1997">
<normalizedToken id="4702C4DEA2561BA0497E089AA6D19D94" originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
et al. 1997
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="D5DBA5EA1D6F19244A6A6EA3DB04FBEB" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megachile</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="20EC15A27331F92E14C4DBDB7F9A9839" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae lagopoda" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagopoda">lagopoda</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EC904981DC05120D793A5FC760FAFACB" genus="M." lsidName="M. maritima" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="maritima">M. maritima</taxonomicName>
are likely polylectic with a preference for 
<taxonomicName id="6360B306F958596794BF54A36B5F1B25" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Fabaceae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FD59898A246B039A8078D4E5242C275B" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Asteraceae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
